              # Chars enables you to work transparently with UTF-8 encoding in the Ruby String class without having extensive
        
      8. 
      
        
    8. 
          
          
              # knowledge about the encoding. A Chars object accepts a string upon initialization and proxies String methods in an
        
      9. 
      
        
    9. 
          
          
              # encoding safe manner. All the normal String methods are also implemented on the proxy.
        
      10. 
      
        
    10. 
          
          
              #
        
      11. 
      
        
    11. 
          
          
              # String methods are proxied through the Chars object, and can be accessed through the +mb_chars+ method. Methods
        
      12. 
      
        
    12. 
          
          
              # which would normally return a String object now return a Chars object so methods can be chained.

                # Like <tt>String#[]=</tt>, except instead of byte offsets you specify character offsets.
        
      254. 
      
        
    254. 
          
          
                #
        
      255. 
      
        
    255. 
          
          
                # Example:
        
      256. 
      
        
    256. 
          
          
                #

    257. 
          
          
                #   s = "Mller"
        
      258.

      259. 
      
        
    259. 
          
          
                #   s
        
      260.

      261. 
      
        
    261. 
          
          
                #
        
      262.

                #   s = "Mller"
        
      263. 
      
        
    263. 
          
          
                #   s.mb_chars[1, 2] = "" # Replace 2 characters at character offset 1
        
      264. 
      
        
    264. 
          
          
                #   s
        
      265. 
      
        
    265. 
          
          
                #   # => "Mler"
        
      266. 
      
        
    266. 
          1
          
                def []=(*args)
        
      267. 
      
        
    267. 
          
          
                  replace_by = args.pop
        
      268. 
      
        
    268. 
          
          
                  # Indexed replace with regular expressions already works
        
      269. 
      
        
    269. 
          
          
                  if args.first.is_a?(Regexp)
        
      270. 
      
        
    270. 
          
          
                    @wrapped_string[*args] = replace_by
        
      271. 
      
        
    271. 
          
          
                  else
        
      272. 
      
        
    272. 
          
          
                    result = Unicode.u_unpack(@wrapped_string)
        
      273. 
      
        
    273. 
          
          
                    case args.first
        
      274. 
      
        
    274. 
          
          
                    when Fixnum
        
      275. 
      
        
    275. 
          
          
                      raise IndexError, "index #{args[0]} out of string" if args[0] >= result.length
        
      276. 
      
        
    276. 
          
          
                      min = args[0]
        
      277. 
      
        
    277. 
          
          
                      max = args[1].nil? ? min : (min + args[1] - 1)
        
      278. 
      
        
    278. 
          
          
                      range = Range.new(min, max)
        
      279. 
      
        
    279. 
          
          
                      replace_by = [replace_by].pack('U') if replace_by.is_a?(Fixnum)
        
      280. 
      
        
    280. 
          
          
                    when Range
        
      281. 
      
        
    281. 
          
          
                      raise RangeError, "#{args[0]} out of range" if args[0].min >= result.length
        
      282. 
      
        
    282. 
          
          
                      range = args[0]
        
      283. 
      
        
    283. 
          
          
                    else
        
      284. 
      
        
    284. 
          
          
                      needle = args[0].to_s
        
      285. 
      
        
    285. 
          
          
                      min = index(needle)
        
      286. 
      
        
    286. 
          
          
                      max = min + Unicode.u_unpack(needle).length - 1
        
      287. 
      
        
    287. 
          
          
                      range = Range.new(min, max)
        
      288. 
      
        
    288. 
          
          
                    end
        
      289. 
      
        
    289. 
          
          
                    result[range] = Unicode.u_unpack(replace_by)
        
      290. 
      
        
    290. 
          
          
                    @wrapped_string.replace(result.pack('U*'))
        
      291. 
      
        
    291. 
          
          
                  end
        
      292. 
      
        
    292. 
          
          
                end
        
      293.

                # Implements Unicode-aware slice with codepoints. Slicing on one point returns the codepoints for that
        
      303. 
      
        
    303. 
          
          
                # character.
        
      304. 
      
        
    304. 
          
          
                #
        
      305. 
      
        
    305. 
          
          
                # Example:
        
      306. 
      
        
    306. 
          
          
                #   ''.mb_chars.slice(2..3).to_s # => ""

    307. 
          1
          
                def slice(*args)
        
      308. 
      
        
    308. 
          
          
                  if args.size > 2
        
      309. 
      
        
    309. 
          
          
                    raise ArgumentError, "wrong number of arguments (#{args.size} for 1)" # Do as if we were native
        
      310. 
      
        
    310. 
          
          
                  elsif (args.size == 2 && !(args.first.is_a?(Numeric) || args.first.is_a?(Regexp)))
        
      311. 
      
        
    311. 
          
          
                    raise TypeError, "cannot convert #{args.first.class} into Integer" # Do as if we were native
        
      312. 
      
        
    312. 
          
          
                  elsif (args.size == 2 && !args[1].is_a?(Numeric))
        
      313. 
      
        
    313. 
          
          
                    raise TypeError, "cannot convert #{args[1].class} into Integer" # Do as if we were native
        
      314. 
      
        
    314. 
          
          
                  elsif args[0].kind_of? Range
        
      315. 
      
        
    315. 
          
          
                    cps = Unicode.u_unpack(@wrapped_string).slice(*args)
        
      316. 
      
        
    316. 
          
          
                    result = cps.nil? ? nil : cps.pack('U*')
        
      317. 
      
        
    317. 
          
          
                  elsif args[0].kind_of? Regexp
        
      318. 
      
        
    318. 
          
          
                    result = @wrapped_string.slice(*args)
        
      319. 
      
        
    319. 
          
          
                  elsif args.size == 1 && args[0].kind_of?(Numeric)
        
      320. 
      
        
    320. 
          
          
                    character = Unicode.u_unpack(@wrapped_string)[args[0]]
        
      321. 
      
        
    321. 
          
          
                    result = character && [character].pack('U')
        
      322. 
      
        
    322. 
          
          
                  else
        
      323. 
      
        
    323. 
          
          
                    cps = Unicode.u_unpack(@wrapped_string).slice(*args)
        
      324. 
      
        
    324. 
          
          
                    result = cps && cps.pack('U*')
        
      325. 
      
        
    325. 
          
          
                  end
        
      326. 
      
        
    326. 
          
          
                  result && chars(result)
        
      327. 
      
        
    327. 
          
          
                end
        
      328. 
      
        
    328. 
          1
          
                alias_method :[], :slice
        
      329.

      330. 
      
        
    330. 
          
          
                # Limit the byte size of the string to a number of bytes without breaking characters. Usable

                # Replaces all ISO-8859-1 or CP1252 characters by their UTF-8 equivalent resulting in a valid UTF-8 string.
        
      411. 
      
        
    411. 
          
          
                #
        
      412. 
      
        
    412. 
          
          
                # Passing +true+ will forcibly tidy all bytes, assuming that the string's encoding is entirely CP1252 or ISO-8859-1.
        
      413.

    416. 
          
          
          
        
      417. 
      
        
    417. 
          1
          
                 %w(capitalize downcase lstrip reverse rstrip slice strip tidy_bytes upcase).each do |method|
        
      418. 
      
        
    418. 
          
          
                  # Only define a corresponding bang method for methods defined in the proxy; On 1.9 the proxy will
        
      419. 
      
        
    419. 
          
          
                  # exclude lstrip!, rstrip! and strip! because they are already work as expected on multibyte strings.
        
      420. 
      
        
    420. 
          9
          
                  if public_method_defined?(method)
        
      421. 
      
        
    421. 
          6
          
                    define_method("#{method}!") do |*args|
        
      422. 
      
        
    422. 
          
          
                      @wrapped_string = send(args.nil? ? method : method, *args).to_s
        
      423. 
      
        
    423. 
          
          
                      self
        
      424. 
      
        
    424. 
          
          
                    end
        
      425. 
      
        
    425. 
          
          
                  end
        
      426. 
      
        
    426. 
          
          
                end

          1
          
                protected
        
      429. 
      
        
    429. 
          
          
          
        
      430. 
      
        
    430. 
          1
          
                  def translate_offset(byte_offset) #:nodoc:
        
      431. 
      
        
    431. 
          
          
                    return nil if byte_offset.nil?
        
      432. 
      
        
    432. 
          
          
                    return 0   if @wrapped_string == ''
        
      433. 
      
        
    433. 
          
          
          
        
      434. 
      
        
    434. 
          
          
                    if @wrapped_string.respond_to?(:force_encoding)
        
      435. 
      
        
    435. 
          
          
                      @wrapped_string = @wrapped_string.dup.force_encoding(Encoding::ASCII_8BIT)
        
      436. 
      
        
    436. 
          
          
                    end
        
      437. 
      
        
    437. 
          
          
          
        
      438. 
      
        
    438. 
          
          
                    begin
        
      439. 
      
        
    439. 
          
          
                      @wrapped_string[0...byte_offset].unpack('U*').length
        
      440. 
      
        
    440. 
          
          
                    rescue ArgumentError
        
      441. 
      
        
    441. 
          
          
                      byte_offset -= 1
        
      442. 
      
        
    442. 
          
          
                      retry
        
      443. 
      
        
    443. 
          
          
                    end
        
      444. 
      
        
    444. 
          
          
                  end
        
      445. 
      
        
    445. 
          
          
          
        
      446. 
      
        
    446. 
          1
          
                  def justify(integer, way, padstr=' ') #:nodoc:
        
      447. 
      
        
    447. 
          
          
                    raise ArgumentError, "zero width padding" if padstr.length == 0
        
      448. 
      
        
    448. 
          
          
                    padsize = integer - size
        
      449. 
      
        
    449. 
          
          
                    padsize = padsize > 0 ? padsize : 0
        
      450. 
      
        
    450. 
          
          
                    case way
        
      451. 
      
        
    451. 
          
          
                    when :right
        
      452. 
      
        
    452. 
          
          
                      result = @wrapped_string.dup.insert(0, padding(padsize, padstr))
        
      453. 
      
        
    453. 
          
          
                    when :left
        
      454. 
      
        
    454. 
          
          
                      result = @wrapped_string.dup.insert(-1, padding(padsize, padstr))
        
      455. 
      
        
    455. 
          
          
                    when :center
        
      456. 
      
        
    456. 
          
          
                      lpad = padding((padsize / 2.0).floor, padstr)
        
      457. 
      
        
    457. 
          
          
                      rpad = padding((padsize / 2.0).ceil, padstr)
        
      458. 
      
        
    458. 
          
          
                      result = @wrapped_string.dup.insert(0, lpad).insert(-1, rpad)
        
      459. 
      
        
    459. 
          
          
                    end
        
      460. 
      
        
    460. 
          
          
                    chars(result)
        
      461. 
      
        
    461. 
          
          
                  end
        
      462. 
      
        
    462. 
          
          
          
        
      463. 
      
        
    463. 
          1
          
                  def padding(padsize, padstr=' ') #:nodoc:
        
      464. 
      
        
    464. 
          
          
                    if padsize != 0
        
      465. 
      
        
    465. 
          
          
                      chars(padstr * ((padsize / Unicode.u_unpack(padstr).size) + 1)).slice(0, padsize)
        
      466. 
      
        
    466. 
          
          
                    else
        
      467. 
      
        
    467. 
          
          
                      ''
        
      468. 
      
        
    468. 
          
          
                    end
        
      469. 
      
        
    469. 
          
          
                  end
        
      470. 
      
        
    470. 
          
          
          
        
      471. 
      
        
    471. 
          1
          
                  def chars(string) #:nodoc:
        
      472. 
      
        
    472. 
          
          
                    self.class.new(string)
        
      473. 
      
        
    473. 
          
          
                  end
        
      474.

              end

            end

          module Diff
        
      4. 
      
        
    4. 
          
          
            # = Diff::LCS 1.1.3
        
      5. 
      
        
    5. 
          
          
            # Computes "intelligent" differences between two sequenced Enumerables.
        
      6. 
      
        
    6. 
          
          
            # This is an implementation of the McIlroy-Hunt "diff" algorithm for
        
      7. 
      
        
    7. 
          
          
            # Enumerable objects that include Diffable.
        
      8. 
      
        
    8. 
          
          
            #
        
      9. 
      
        
    9. 
          
          
            # Based on Mario I. Wolczko's Smalltalk version (1.2, 1993) and Ned Konz's
        
      10. 
      
        
    10. 
          
          
            # Perl version (Algorithm::Diff 1.15).
        
      11. 
      
        
    11. 
          
          
            #
        
      12. 
      
        
    12. 
          
          
            # == Synopsis
        
      13. 
      
        
    13. 
          
          
            #   require 'diff/lcs'
        
      14. 
      
        
    14. 
          
          
            #
        
      15. 
      
        
    15. 
          
          
            #   seq1 = %w(a b c e h j l m n p)
        
      16. 
      
        
    16. 
          
          
            #   seq2 = %w(b c d e f j k l m r s t)
        
      17. 
      
        
    17. 
          
          
            #
        
      18. 
      
        
    18. 
          
          
            #   lcs = Diff::LCS.LCS(seq1, seq2)
        
      19. 
      
        
    19. 
          
          
            #   diffs = Diff::LCS.diff(seq1, seq2)
        
      20. 
      
        
    20. 
          
          
            #   sdiff = Diff::LCS.sdiff(seq1, seq2)
        
      21. 
      
        
    21. 
          
          
            #   seq = Diff::LCS.traverse_sequences(seq1, seq2, callback_obj)
        
      22. 
      
        
    22. 
          
          
            #   bal = Diff::LCS.traverse_balanced(seq1, seq2, callback_obj)
        
      23. 
      
        
    23. 
          
          
            #   seq2 == Diff::LCS.patch(seq1, diffs)
        
      24. 
      
        
    24. 
          
          
            #   seq2 == Diff::LCS.patch!(seq1, diffs)
        
      25. 
      
        
    25. 
          
          
            #   seq1 == Diff::LCS.unpatch(seq2, diffs)
        
      26. 
      
        
    26. 
          
          
            #   seq1 == Diff::LCS.unpatch!(seq2, diffs)
        
      27. 
      
        
    27. 
          
          
            #   seq2 == Diff::LCS.patch(seq1, sdiff)
        
      28. 
      
        
    28. 
          
          
            #   seq2 == Diff::LCS.patch!(seq1, sdiff)
        
      29. 
      
        
    29. 
          
          
            #   seq1 == Diff::LCS.unpatch(seq2, sdiff)
        
      30. 
      
        
    30. 
          
          
            #   seq1 == Diff::LCS.unpatch!(seq2, sdiff)
        
      31. 
      
        
    31. 
          
          
            #
        
      32. 
      
        
    32. 
          
          
            # Alternatively, objects can be extended with Diff::LCS:
        
      33. 
      
        
    33. 
          
          
            #
        
      34. 
      
        
    34. 
          
          
            #   seq1.extend(Diff::LCS)
        
      35. 
      
        
    35. 
          
          
            #   lcs = seq1.lcs(seq2)
        
      36. 
      
        
    36. 
          
          
            #   diffs = seq1.diff(seq2)
        
      37. 
      
        
    37. 
          
          
            #   sdiff = seq1.sdiff(seq2)
        
      38. 
      
        
    38. 
          
          
            #   seq = seq1.traverse_sequences(seq2, callback_obj)
        
      39. 
      
        
    39. 
          
          
            #   bal = seq1.traverse_balanced(seq2, callback_obj)
        
      40. 
      
        
    40. 
          
          
            #   seq2 == seq1.patch(diffs)
        
      41. 
      
        
    41. 
          
          
            #   seq2 == seq1.patch!(diffs)
        
      42. 
      
        
    42. 
          
          
            #   seq1 == seq2.unpatch(diffs)
        
      43. 
      
        
    43. 
          
          
            #   seq1 == seq2.unpatch!(diffs)
        
      44. 
      
        
    44. 
          
          
            #   seq2 == seq1.patch(sdiff)
        
      45. 
      
        
    45.

            # Default extensions are provided for Array and String objects through the
        
      50. 
      
        
    50.

      51.

            # == Introduction (by Mark-Jason Dominus)
        
      53. 
      
        
    53. 
          
          
            # 
        
      54. 
      
        
    54. 
          
          
            # <em>The following text is from the Perl documentation. The only changes
        
      55. 
      
        
    55. 
          
          
            # have been to make the text appear better in Rdoc</em>.
        
      56. 
      
        
    56. 
          
          
            #
        
      57. 
      
        
    57. 
          
          
            # I once read an article written by the authors of +diff+; they said that
        
      58. 
      
        
    58. 
          
          
            # they hard worked very hard on the algorithm until they found the right
        
      59. 
      
        
    59. 
          
          
            # one.
        
      60. 
      
        
    60. 
          
          
            #
        
      61. 
      
        
    61. 
          
          
            # I think what they ended up using (and I hope someone will correct me,
        
      62. 
      
        
    62. 
          
          
            # because I am not very confident about this) was the `longest common
        
      63. 
      
        
    63. 
          
          
            # subsequence' method. In the LCS problem, you have two sequences of
        
      64. 
      
        
    64. 
          
          
            # items:
        
      65. 
      
        
    65. 
          
          
            #
        
      66. 
      
        
    66. 
          
          
            #    a b c d f g h j q z
        
      67. 
      
        
    67. 
          
          
            #    a b c d e f g i j k r x y z
        
      68. 
      
        
    68. 
          
          
            #
        
      69. 
      
        
    69. 
          
          
            # and you want to find the longest sequence of items that is present in
        
      70. 
      
        
    70. 
          
          
            # both original sequences in the same order. That is, you want to find a
        
      71. 
      
        
    71. 
          
          
            # new sequence *S* which can be obtained from the first sequence by
        
      72. 
      
        
    72. 
          
          
            # deleting some items, and from the second sequence by deleting other
        
      73. 
      
        
    73. 
          
          
            # items. You also want *S* to be as long as possible. In this case *S* is:
        
      74. 
      
        
    74. 
          
          
            # 
        
      75. 
      
        
    75. 
          
          
            #    a b c d f g j z
        
      76. 
      
        
    76. 
          
          
            #
        
      77. 
      
        
    77. 
          
          
            # From there it's only a small step to get diff-like output:
        
      78. 
      
        
    78. 
          
          
            #
        
      79. 
      
        
    79. 
          
          
            #    e   h i   k   q r x y
        
      80. 
      
        
    80. 
          
          
            #    +   - +   +   - + + +
        
      81. 
      
        
    81. 
          
          
            #
        
      82. 
      
        
    82. 
          
          
            # This module solves the LCS problem. It also includes a canned function
        
      83. 
      
        
    83. 
          
          
            # to generate +diff+-like output.
        
      84. 
      
        
    84. 
          
          
            #
        
      85. 
      
        
    85. 
          
          
            # It might seem from the example above that the LCS of two sequences is
        
      86. 
      
        
    86. 
          
          
            # always pretty obvious, but that's not always the case, especially when
        
      87. 
      
        
    87. 
          
          
            # the two sequences have many repeated elements. For example, consider
        
      88. 
      
        
    88. 
          
          
            #
        
      89. 
      
        
    89. 
          
          
            #    a x b y c z p d q
        
      90. 
      
        
    90. 
          
          
            #    a b c a x b y c z
        
      91. 
      
        
    91. 
          
          
            #
        
      92. 
      
        
    92. 
          
          
            # A naive approach might start by matching up the +a+ and +b+ that appear
        
      93. 
      
        
    93. 
          
          
            # at the beginning of each sequence, like this:
        
      94. 
      
        
    94. 
          
          
            # 
        
      95. 
      
        
    95. 
          
          
            #    a x b y c         z p d q
        
      96. 
      
        
    96. 
          
          
            #    a   b   c a b y c z
        
      97. 
      
        
    97. 
          
          
            #
        
      98. 
      
        
    98. 
          
          
            # This finds the common subsequence +a b c z+. But actually, the LCS is
        
      99. 
      
        
    99. 
          
          
            # +a x b y c z+:
        
      100. 
      
        
    100. 
          
          
            #
        
      101. 
      
        
    101. 
          
          
            #          a x b y c z p d q
        
      102. 
      
        
    102. 
          
          
            #    a b c a x b y c z
        
      103. 
      
        
    103. 
          
          
            #
        
      104. 
      
        
    104.
