          # private
        
      795. 
      
        
    795. 
          
          
              # Compute the longest common subsequence between the sequenced
        
      796. 
      
        
    796. 
          
          
              # Enumerables +a+ and +b+. The result is an array whose contents is such
        
      797. 
      
        
    797. 
          
          
              # that
        
      798. 
      
        
    798. 
          
          
              #
        
      799. 
      
        
    799. 
          
          
              #     result = Diff::LCS.__lcs(a, b)
        
      800. 
      
        
    800. 
          
          
              #     result.each_with_index do |e, ii|
        
      801. 
      
        
    801. 
          
          
              #       assert_equal(a[ii], b[e]) unless e.nil?
        
      802. 
      
        
    802. 
          
          
              #     end
        
      803. 
      
        
    803. 
          
          
              #
        
      804. 
      
        
    804. 
          
          
              # Note: This will be deprecated as a public function in a future release.
        
      805. 
      
        
    805. 
          1
          
              def __lcs(a, b)
        
      806. 
      
        
    806. 
          
          
                a_start = b_start = 0
        
      807. 
      
        
    807. 
          
          
                a_finish = a.size - 1
        
      808. 
      
        
    808. 
          
          
                b_finish = b.size - 1
        
      809. 
      
        
    809. 
          
          
                vector = []
        
      810. 
      
        
    810. 
          
          
          
        
      811. 
      
        
    811. 
          
          
                # Prune off any common elements at the beginning...
        
      812. 
      
        
    812. 
          
          
                while (a_start <= a_finish) and
        
      813. 
      
        
    813. 
          
          
                  (b_start <= b_finish) and
        
      814. 
      
        
    814. 
          
          
                  (a[a_start] == b[b_start])
        
      815. 
      
        
    815. 
          
          
                  vector[a_start] = b_start
        
      816. 
      
        
    816. 
          
          
                  a_start += 1
        
      817. 
      
        
    817. 
          
          
                  b_start += 1
        
      818. 
      
        
    818. 
          
          
                end
        
      819. 
      
        
    819. 
          
          
          
        
      820. 
      
        
    820. 
          
          
                # Now the end...
        
      821. 
      
        
    821. 
          
          
                while (a_start <= a_finish) and
        
      822. 
      
        
    822. 
          
          
                  (b_start <= b_finish) and
        
      823. 
      
        
    823. 
          
          
                  (a[a_finish] == b[b_finish])
        
      824. 
      
        
    824. 
          
          
                  vector[a_finish] = b_finish
        
      825. 
      
        
    825. 
          
          
                  a_finish -= 1
        
      826. 
      
        
    826. 
          
          
                  b_finish -= 1
        
      827. 
      
        
    827. 
          
          
                end
        
      828. 
      
        
    828. 
          
          
          
        
      829. 
      
        
    829. 
          
          
                # Now, compute the equivalence classes of positions of elements.
        
      830. 
      
        
    830. 
          
          
                b_matches = Diff::LCS.__position_hash(b, b_start .. b_finish)
        
      831. 
      
        
    831. 
          
          
          
        
      832. 
      
        
    832. 
          
          
                thresh = []
        
      833. 
      
        
    833. 
          
          
                links = []
        
      834. 
      
        
    834. 
          
          
          
        
      835. 
      
        
    835. 
          
          
                (a_start .. a_finish).each do |ii|
        
      836. 
      
        
    836. 
          
          
                  ai = a.kind_of?(String) ? a[ii, 1] : a[ii]
        
      837. 
      
        
    837. 
          
          
                  bm = b_matches[ai]
        
      838. 
      
        
    838. 
          
          
                  kk = nil
        
      839. 
      
        
    839. 
          
          
                  bm.reverse_each do |jj|
        
      840. 
      
        
    840. 
          
          
                    if kk and (thresh[kk] > jj) and (thresh[kk - 1] < jj)
        
      841. 
      
        
    841. 
          
          
                      thresh[kk] = jj
        
      842. 
      
        
    842. 
          
          
                    else
        
      843. 
      
        
    843. 
          
          
                      kk = Diff::LCS.__replace_next_larger(thresh, jj, kk)
        
      844. 
      
        
    844. 
          
          
                    end
        
      845. 
      
        
    845. 
          
          
                    links[kk] = [ (kk > 0) ? links[kk - 1] : nil, ii, jj ] unless kk.nil?
        
      846. 
      
        
    846. 
          
          
                  end
        
      847. 
      
        
    847. 
          
          
                end
        
      848. 
      
        
    848. 
          
          
          
        
      849. 
      
        
    849. 
          
          
                unless thresh.empty?
        
      850. 
      
        
    850. 
          
          
                  link = links[thresh.size - 1]
        
      851. 
      
        
    851. 
          
          
                  while not link.nil?
        
      852. 
      
        
    852. 
          
          
                    vector[link[1]] = link[2]
        
      853. 
      
        
    853. 
          
          
                    link = link[0]
        
      854. 
      
        
    854. 
          
          
                  end
        
      855. 
      
        
    855. 
          
          
                end
        
      856. 
      
        
    856. 
          
          
          
        
      857. 
      
        
    857. 
          
          
                vector
        
      858. 
      
        
    858. 
          
          
              end
        
      859. 
      
        
    859. 
          
          
          
        
      860. 
      
        
    860. 
          
          
              # Find the place at which +value+ would normally be inserted into the
        
      861. 
      
        
    861. 
          
          
              # Enumerable. If that place is already occupied by +value+, do nothing
        
      862. 
      
        
    862. 
          
          
              # and return +nil+. If the place does not exist (i.e., it is off the end
        
      863. 
      
        
    863. 
          
          
              # of the Enumerable), add it to the end. Otherwise, replace the element
        
      864. 
      
        
    864. 
          
          
              # at that point with +value+. It is assumed that the Enumerable's values
        
      865. 
      
        
    865. 
          
          
              # are numeric.
        
      866. 
      
        
    866. 
          
          
              #
        
      867. 
      
        
    867. 
          
          
              # This operation preserves the sort order.
        
      868. 
      
        
    868. 
          
          
              #
        
      869. 
      
        
    869. 
          
          
              # Note: This will be deprecated as a public function in a future release.
        
      870. 
      
        
    870. 
          1
          
              def __replace_next_larger(enum, value, last_index = nil)
        
      871. 
      
        
    871. 
          
          
                  # Off the end?
        
      872. 
      
        
    872. 
          
          
                if enum.empty? or (value > enum[-1])
        
      873. 
      
        
    873. 
          
          
                  enum << value
        
      874. 
      
        
    874. 
          
          
                  return enum.size - 1
        
      875. 
      
        
    875. 
          
          
                end
        
      876. 
      
        
    876. 
          
          
          
        
      877. 
      
        
    877. 
          
          
                  # Binary search for the insertion point
        
      878. 
      
        
    878. 
          
          
                last_index ||= enum.size
        
      879. 
      
        
    879. 
          
          
                first_index = 0
        
      880. 
      
        
    880. 
          
          
                while (first_index <= last_index)
        
      881. 
      
        
    881. 
          
          
                  ii = (first_index + last_index) >> 1
        
      882. 
      
        
    882. 
          
          
          
        
      883. 
      
        
    883. 
          
          
                  found = enum[ii]
        
      884. 
      
        
    884. 
          
          
          
        
      885. 
      
        
    885. 
          
          
                  if value == found
        
      886. 
      
        
    886. 
          
          
                    return nil
        
      887. 
      
        
    887. 
          
          
                  elsif value > found
        
      888. 
      
        
    888. 
          
          
                    first_index = ii + 1
        
      889. 
      
        
    889. 
          
          
                  else
        
      890. 
      
        
    890. 
          
          
                    last_index = ii - 1
        
      891. 
      
        
    891. 
          
          
                  end
        
      892. 
      
        
    892. 
          
          
                end
        
      893. 
      
        
    893. 
          
          
          
        
      894. 
      
        
    894. 
          
          
                  # The insertion point is in first_index; overwrite the next larger
        
      895. 
      
        
    895. 
          
          
                  # value.
        
      896. 
      
        
    896. 
          
          
                enum[first_index] = value
        
      897. 
      
        
    897. 
          
          
                return first_index
        
      898. 
      
        
    898. 
          
          
              end
        
      899. 
      
        
    899. 
          
          
          
        
      900. 
      
        
    900. 
          
          
              # If +vector+ maps the matching elements of another collection onto this
        
      901. 
      
        
    901. 
          
          
              # Enumerable, compute the inverse +vector+ that maps this Enumerable
        
      902. 
      
        
    902. 
          
          
              # onto the collection. (Currently unused.)
        
      903. 
      
        
    903. 
          
          
              #
        
      904. 
      
        
    904. 
          
          
              # Note: This will be deprecated as a public function in a future release.
        
      905. 
      
        
    905. 
          1
          
              def __inverse_vector(a, vector)
        
      906. 
      
        
    906. 
          
          
                inverse = a.dup
        
      907. 
      
        
    907. 
          
          
                (0 ... vector.size).each do |ii|
        
      908. 
      
        
    908. 
          
          
                  inverse[vector[ii]] = ii unless vector[ii].nil?
        
      909. 
      
        
    909. 
          
          
                end
        
      910. 
      
        
    910. 
          
          
                inverse
        
      911. 
      
        
    911. 
          
          
              end
        
      912. 
      
        
    912. 
          
          
          
        
      913. 
      
        
    913. 
          
          
              # Returns a hash mapping each element of an Enumerable to the set of
        
      914. 
      
        
    914. 
          
          
              # positions it occupies in the Enumerable, optionally restricted to the
        
      915. 
      
        
    915. 
          
          
              # elements specified in the range of indexes specified by +interval+.
        
      916. 
      
        
    916. 
          
          
              #
        
      917. 
      
        
    917. 
          
          
              # Note: This will be deprecated as a public function in a future release.
        
      918. 
      
        
    918. 
          1
          
              def __position_hash(enum, interval = 0 .. -1)
        
      919. 
      
        
    919. 
          
          
                hash = Hash.new { |hh, kk| hh[kk] = [] }
        
      920. 
      
        
    920. 
          
          
                interval.each do |ii|
        
      921. 
      
        
    921. 
          
          
                  kk = enum.kind_of?(String) ? enum[ii, 1] : enum[ii]
        
      922. 
      
        
    922. 
          
          
                  hash[kk] << ii
        
      923. 
      
        
    923. 
          
          
                end
        
      924. 
      
        
    924. 
          
          
                hash
        
      925. 
      
        
    925. 
          
          
              end
        
      926. 
      
        
    926. 
          
          
          
        
      927. 
      
        
    927. 
          
          
              # Examine the patchset and the source to see in which direction the
        
      928. 
      
        
    928. 
          
          
              # patch should be applied.
        
      929. 
      
        
    929. 
          
          
              #
        
      930. 
      
        
    930. 
          
          
              # WARNING: By default, this examines the whole patch, so this could take
        
      931. 
      
        
    931. 
          
          
              # some time. This also works better with Diff::LCS::ContextChange or
        
      932. 
      
        
    932. 
          
          
              # Diff::LCS::Change as its source, as an array will cause the creation
        
      933. 
      
        
    933. 
          
          
              # of one of the above.
        
      934. 
      
        
    934. 
          
          
              #
        
      935. 
      
        
    935. 
          
          
              # Note: This will be deprecated as a public function in a future release.
        
      936. 
      
        
    936. 
          1
          
              def __diff_direction(src, patchset, limit = nil)
        
      937. 
      
        
    937. 
          
          
                count = left = left_miss = right = right_miss = 0
        
      938. 
      
        
    938. 
          
          
                string = src.kind_of?(String)
        
      939. 
      
        
    939. 
          
          
          
        
      940. 
      
        
    940. 
          
          
                patchset.each do |change|
        
      941. 
      
        
    941. 
          
          
                  count += 1
        
      942. 
      
        
    942. 
          
          
          
        
      943. 
      
        
    943. 
          
          
                  case change
        
      944. 
      
        
    944. 
          
          
                  when Diff::LCS::Change
        
      945. 
      
        
    945. 
          
          
                    # With a simplistic change, we can't tell the difference between
        
      946. 
      
        
    946. 
          
          
                    # the left and right on '!' actions, so we ignore those. On '='
        
      947. 
      
        
    947. 
          
          
                    # actions, if there's a miss, we miss both left and right.
        
      948. 
      
        
    948. 
          
          
                    element = string ? src[change.position, 1] : src[change.position]
        
      949. 
      
        
    949. 
          
          
          
        
      950. 
      
        
    950. 
          
          
                    case change.action
        
      951. 
      
        
    951. 
          
          
                    when '-'
        
      952. 
      
        
    952. 
          
          
                      if element == change.element
        
      953. 
      
        
    953. 
          
          
                        left += 1
        
      954. 
      
        
    954. 
          
          
                      else
        
      955. 
      
        
    955. 
          
          
                        left_miss += 1
        
      956. 
      
        
    956. 
          
          
                      end
        
      957. 
      
        
    957. 
          
          
                    when '+'
        
      958. 
      
        
    958. 
          
          
                      if element == change.element
        
      959. 
      
        
    959. 
          
          
                        right += 1
        
      960. 
      
        
    960. 
          
          
                      else
        
      961. 
      
        
    961. 
          
          
                        right_miss += 1
        
      962. 
      
        
    962. 
          
          
                      end
        
      963. 
      
        
    963. 
          
          
                    when '='
        
      964. 
      
        
    964. 
          
          
                      if element != change.element
        
      965. 
      
        
    965. 
          
          
                        left_miss += 1
        
      966. 
      
        
    966. 
          
          
                        right_miss += 1
        
      967. 
      
        
    967. 
          
          
                      end
        
      968. 
      
        
    968. 
          
          
                    end
        
      969. 
      
        
    969. 
          
          
                  when Diff::LCS::ContextChange
        
      970. 
      
        
    970. 
          
          
                    case change.action
        
      971. 
      
        
    971. 
          
          
                    when '-' # Remove details from the old string
        
      972. 
      
        
    972. 
          
          
                      element = string ? src[change.old_position, 1] : src[change.old_position]
        
      973. 
      
        
    973. 
          
          
                      if element == change.old_element
        
      974. 
      
        
    974. 
          
          
                        left += 1
        
      975. 
      
        
    975. 
          
          
                      else
        
      976. 
      
        
    976. 
          
          
                        left_miss += 1
        
      977. 
      
        
    977. 
          
          
                      end
        
      978. 
      
        
    978. 
          
          
                    when '+'
        
      979. 
      
        
    979. 
          
          
                      element = string ? src[change.new_position, 1] : src[change.new_position]
        
      980. 
      
        
    980. 
          
          
                      if element == change.new_element
        
      981. 
      
        
    981. 
          
          
                        right += 1
        
      982. 
      
        
    982. 
          
          
                      else
        
      983. 
      
        
    983. 
          
          
                        right_miss += 1
        
      984. 
      
        
    984. 
          
          
                      end
        
      985. 
      
        
    985. 
          
          
                    when '='
        
      986. 
      
        
    986. 
          
          
                      le = string ? src[change.old_position, 1] : src[change.old_position]
        
      987. 
      
        
    987. 
          
          
                      re = string ? src[change.new_position, 1] : src[change.new_position]
        
      988. 
      
        
    988. 
          
          
          
        
      989. 
      
        
    989. 
          
          
                      left_miss += 1 if le != change.old_element
        
      990. 
      
        
    990. 
          
          
                      right_miss += 1 if re != change.new_element
        
      991. 
      
        
    991. 
          
          
                    when '!'
        
      992. 
      
        
    992. 
          
          
                      element = string ? src[change.old_position, 1] : src[change.old_position]
        
      993. 
      
        
    993. 
          
          
                      if element == change.old_element
        
      994. 
      
        
    994. 
          
          
                        left += 1
        
      995. 
      
        
    995. 
          
          
                      else
        
      996. 
      
        
    996. 
          
          
                        element = string ? src[change.new_position, 1] : src[change.new_position]
        
      997. 
      
        
    997. 
          
          
                        if element == change.new_element
        
      998. 
      
        
    998. 
          
          
                          right += 1
        
      999. 
      
        
    999. 
          
          
                        else
        
      1000. 
      
        
    1000. 
          
          
                          left_miss += 1
        
      1001. 
      
        
    1001. 
          
          
                          right_miss += 1
        
      1002. 
      
        
    1002. 
          
          
                        end
        
      1003. 
      
        
    1003.

            # This will produce a compound array of contextual diff change objects. Each
        
      150. 
      
        
    150. 
          
          
            # element in the #diffs array is a "hunk" array, where each element in each
        
      151. 
      
        
    151. 
          
          
            # "hunk" array is a single change. Each change is a Diff::LCS::ContextChange
        
      152. 
      
        
    152. 
          
          
            # that contains both the old index and new index values for the change. The
        
      153. 
      
        
    153. 
          
          
            # "hunk" provides the full context for the changes. Both old and new objects
        
      154. 
      
        
    154. 
          
          
            # will be presented for changed objects. +nil+ will be substituted for a
        
      155. 
      
        
    155. 
          
          
            # discarded object.
        
      156. 
      
        
    156. 
          
          
            #
        
      157. 
      
        
    157. 
          
          
            #     seq1 = %w(a b c e h j l m n p)
        
      158. 
      
        
    158. 
          
          
            #     seq2 = %w(b c d e f j k l m r s t)
        
      159. 
      
        
    159. 
          
          
            #
        
      160. 
      
        
    160. 
          
          
            #     diffs = Diff::LCS.diff(seq1, seq2, Diff::LCS::ContextDiffCallbacks)
        
      161. 
      
        
    161. 
          
          
            #       # This example shows a simplified array format.
        
      162. 
      
        
    162. 
          
          
            #       # [ [ [ '-', [  0, 'a' ], [  0, nil ] ] ],   # 1
        
      163. 
      
        
    163. 
          
          
            #       #   [ [ '+', [  3, nil ], [  2, 'd' ] ] ],   # 2
        
      164. 
      
        
    164. 
          
          
            #       #   [ [ '-', [  4, 'h' ], [  4, nil ] ],     # 3
        
      165. 
      
        
    165. 
          
          
            #       #     [ '+', [  5, nil ], [  4, 'f' ] ] ],
        
      166. 
      
        
    166. 
          
          
            #       #   [ [ '+', [  6, nil ], [  6, 'k' ] ] ],   # 4
        
      167. 
      
        
    167. 
          
          
            #       #   [ [ '-', [  8, 'n' ], [  9, nil ] ],     # 5
        
      168. 
      
        
    168. 
          
          
            #       #     [ '+', [  9, nil ], [  9, 'r' ] ],
        
      169. 
      
        
    169. 
          
          
            #       #     [ '-', [  9, 'p' ], [ 10, nil ] ],
        
      170. 
      
        
    170. 
          
          
            #       #     [ '+', [ 10, nil ], [ 10, 's' ] ],
        
      171. 
      
        
    171. 
          
          
            #       #     [ '+', [ 10, nil ], [ 11, 't' ] ] ] ]
        
      172. 
      
        
    172. 
          
          
            #
        
      173. 
      
        
    173. 
          
          
            # The five hunks shown are comprised of individual changes; if there is a
        
      174. 
      
        
    174. 
          
          
            # related set of changes, they are still shown individually.
        
      175. 
      
        
    175. 
          
          
            #
        
      176. 
      
        
    176. 
          
          
            # This callback can also be used with Diff::LCS#sdiff, which will produce
        
      177. 
      
        
    177. 
          
          
            # results like:
        
      178. 
      
        
    178. 
          
          
            #
        
      179.

            #     diffs = Diff::LCS.sdiff(seq1, seq2, Diff::LCS::ContextCallbacks)
        
      180. 
      
        
    180. 
          
          
            #       # This example shows a simplified array format.
        
      181. 
      
        
    181. 
          
          
            #       # [ [ [ "-", [  0, "a" ], [  0, nil ] ] ],  # 1
        
      182. 
      
        
    182. 
          
          
            #       #   [ [ "+", [  3, nil ], [  2, "d" ] ] ],  # 2
        
      183. 
      
        
    183. 
          
          
            #       #   [ [ "!", [  4, "h" ], [  4, "f" ] ] ],  # 3
        
      184. 
      
        
    184. 
          
          
            #       #   [ [ "+", [  6, nil ], [  6, "k" ] ] ],  # 4
        
      185. 
      
        
    185. 
          
          
            #       #   [ [ "!", [  8, "n" ], [  9, "r" ] ],    # 5
        
      186. 
      
        
    186. 
          
          
            #       #     [ "!", [  9, "p" ], [ 10, "s" ] ],
        
      187. 
      
        
    187. 
          
          
            #       #     [ "+", [ 10, nil ], [ 11, "t" ] ] ] ]
        
      188. 
      
        
    188. 
          
          
            #
        
      189. 
      
        
    189. 
          
          
            # The five hunks are still present, but are significantly shorter in total
        
      190. 
      
        
    190. 
          
          
            # presentation, because changed items are shown as changes ("!") instead of
        
      191.

      192. 
      
        
    192. 
          
          
            #

      194.

      197.

            #     c = Diff::LCS.sdiff(seq1, seq2, Diff::LCS::ContextDiffCallbacks).flatten
        
      198. 
      
        
    198.

      199.

      200.

            # This will produce a simple array of diff change objects. Each element in
        
      237. 
      
        
    237. 
          
          
            # the #diffs array is a single ContextChange. In the set of #diffs provided
        
      238. 
      
        
    238. 
          
          
            # by SDiffCallbacks, both old and new objects will be presented for both
        
      239. 
      
        
    239.

      240. 
      
        
    240. 
          
          
            # for a discarded object.
        
      241. 
      
        
    241. 
          
          
            #
        
      242. 
      
        
    242. 
          
          
            # The diffset produced by this callback, when provided to Diff::LCS#sdiff,
        
      243. 
      
        
    243. 
          
          
            # will compute and display the necessary components to show two sequences
        
      244. 
      
        
    244.

      245. 
      
        
    245. 
          
          
            # +sdiff+.
        
      246. 
      
        
    246. 
          
          
            # 
        
      247.

            #     same             same

      249. 
      
        
    249.

      250. 
      
        
    250. 
          
          
            #     -          >     new
        
      251. 
      
        
    251. 
          
          
            #
        
      252. 
      
        
    252. 
          
          
            #     seq1 = %w(a b c e h j l m n p)

    253.

      254.

            def self.simplify(event)
        
      150. 
      
        
    150. 
          
          
              ea = event.to_a
        
      151.

      152.

              case ea[0]
        
      153.

              when '-'
        
      154. 
      
        
    154. 
          
          
                ea[2][1] = nil
        
      155. 
      
        
    155. 
          
          
              when '<'
        
      156. 
      
        
    156. 
          
          
                ea[0] = '-'
        
      157. 
      
        
    157. 
          
          
                ea[2][1] = nil
        
      158. 
      
        
    158. 
          
          
              when '+'
        
      159. 
      
        
    159. 
          
          
                ea[1][1] = nil
        
      160. 
      
        
    160. 
          
          
              when '>'
        
      161. 
      
        
    161. 
          
          
                ea[0] = '+'
        
      162. 
      
        
    162. 
          
          
                ea[1][1] = nil
        
      163. 
      
        
    163. 
          
          
              end
        
      164. 
      
        
    164. 
          
          
          
        
      165.

            def context_range(mode)
        
      217. 
      
        
    217. 
          
          
              case mode
        
      218. 
      
        
    218.

    220.

      221. 
      
        
    221.

      222. 
      
        
    222. 
          
          
              end
        
      223. 
      
        
    223. 
          
          
          
        
      224.

            end
        
      226. 
      
        
    226. 
          
          
          
        
      227. 
      
        
    227.

      228.

    230. 
          1
          
            def unified_range(mode)
        
      231. 
      
        
    231. 
          
          
              case mode
        
      232.

    234.

      235. 
      
        
    235. 
          
          
                s, e = (@start_new + 1), (@end_new + 1)
        
      236. 
      
        
    236. 
          
          
              end
        
      237. 
      
        
    237. 
          
          
          
        
      238. 
      
        
    238. 
          
          
              length = e - s + 1
        
      239. 
      
        
    239. 
          
          
              first = (length < 2) ? e : s # "strange, but correct"

            #

            # Both methods take an optional matcher object (See

    17. 
          
          
            # [RSpec::Matchers](../RSpec/Matchers)).  When `should` is invoked with a
        
      18. 
      
        
    18. 
          
          
            # matcher, it turns around and calls `matcher.matches?(self)`.  For example,
        
      19.

            # in the expression:
        
      20.

            #

    23. 
          
          
            # the `should` method invokes the equivalent of `eq.matches?(order.total)`. If
        
      24. 
      
        
    24. 
          
          
            # `matches?` returns true, the expectation is met and execution continues. If
        
      25. 
      
        
    25. 
          
          
            # `false`, then the spec fails with the message returned by
        
      26. 
      
        
    26. 
          
          
            # `eq.failure_message_for_should`.
        
      27.

            # the `should_not` method invokes the equivalent of
        
      33.

      34.

      35.

      36.
